{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580357/1948110401/0274.xml":{"full_text":"i\nft:\n,s\n1\n'2\nI\ni\n1\nII\n1\ns\nI\ni\n4\n-f\nI\nk\ns\nI\n't\nChicago Printers Plan New Moves\nIn Strike Against Daily Papers\nChicago, (ILNS).\u2014Union print\ners are planning new moves in\ntheir strike against the daily news\npapers here. s\nChicago Typographical tj n ion\nNo. 16 is holding a conference of\nrepresentatives of local unions of\nthe International. Typographical\nUnion dealing with the Hearst\nnewspapers to work out common\nproblems of defense.\nHearst Paper Intransigent\nThe union pointed out that the\nmanagement of the local Hearst\npaper, the Herald-American, has\n\u201crefused to grunt the printers in\nChicago the same union security it\nhas granted to printers belonging\nto the ITU in a dozen other towns\nwhere Hearst owns newspapers.\u201d\nIt added:\n\u201cWe proposed to the Herald-Am\nerican the identical union-security\ncontract agreed to by the Hearst\nmanagement as legal in New York.\nBut they refu~o to give union print\ners in Chicago what they gave un\nion printers in New York.\u201d\nMeanwhile, the union is of course\ncontinuing its campaign against\nthe Chicago Newspaper Publishers\u2019\nAssociation and especially its boy\n\u2018cott campaign against the Herald-\nAmerican. Developments in its\nstrike, now almost a year old, con\nstitute the best illustration of the\nunwuiliability of the Taft-Hartley\nlaw, it was pointed out.\n\u201cHere for 95 years we were able\n'to negotiate satisfactory agree\nments with our newspaper employ\ners in Chicago,\u201d N. M. Di Pietro,\nexecutive secretary of the Chicago\nFederation of Printing Trudes Un\nions, said over the Chicago Federa\ntion of Labor radio station, WCFL,\non the union\u2019s program, \u201cMeet the\nUnion Printers.\u201d\n95-Year Peace Record Cited\n\u201cSometimes there were differ\nences,\u201d he said, \u201cbut they were al\nways resolved without a strike.\nThis time, the parties found it im\npossible to do so. And for nearly a\nyear, our union has been plagued\nwith National Labor Relations\nBoard persecution, congressional in\nvestigations, court proceedings, in\njunction orders, contempt citations,\nand numerous other efforts to di\nvide our international union from\nour local unions, and our interna\ntional and local union officials from\nour general membership. Through\nout the rest of the country news\npaper publishers, without violating\nthe law but also with no desire to\ntear at the structure of our organ\nization have found it possible to\ncontinue living and working har\nmoniously with our local unions.\u201d\nTurning to the Chicago situation.\nDi Pietro stated that \u201cwe are in\nagreement with the publishers on\nmany provisions of the contract\u201d\nand have proposed that \u201cclauses\nsimilar to those in the New York\ncontract be agreed upon to cover\nprovisions still in dispute.\u201d Federal\nJudge Luther M. Swygert in issu\ning the contempt citation against\nthe ITU, \u2018has held that the pro\nposed clauses and the New York\ncontract do not violate the injunc\ntion decree of March 27,\u201d he said,\nand asserted that, \u201ctherefore, there\nis no valid reason why the publish-\nYou Can See the Cream\nALWAYS USE\nCREAM TOP\nMilk Bottles\nGolden Star\nA Dairy\nPhone 3200\nTHEY ARE SANITARY\nUsed Exclusively By\n\u2022i.\nunera\nvW) sts\nDawson\n\u201cso\ners in good conscience cannot pro\nceed to negotiate in good faith\u201d\nwith No. 16 along the lines of the\nunion\u2019s proposal.\nITU Steps \u201cFrozen\u201d\nJudge Sherman Minton and J.\nEarl Major of the United States\nCircuit Court of Appeals here have\nsigned an order staying the execu\ntion of the contempt citation. This\nfollows Judge Swygert\u2019s refusal,\nafter a hearing lasting only 20\nminutes, to grant such a stay, on\nthe grounds that any delay in\ncarrying out his contempt order\ncould be contrary to the public in\nterest. Union attorneys argued that\nthe general union membership\nwould suffer irreparable injury if\nthe ITU were compelled to comply\nat once with Judge Swygert\u2019s\norder, and NLRB attorneys opposed\nthe union\u2019s position.\nDi Pietro, in his broadcast, ex\nplained that the effect of the order\nsigned by Judges Minton and Maj\nor is to \u201cfreeze\u2014at least tempor\narily\u2014-any steps by the ITU in\ncomplying with Judge Swygert\u2019s\nI \"ontempt order.\u201d He said, however,\nthat the judges made it \u201cclear that\ntheir action was without'prejudice\nto the right of the attorneys for the\nNLRB to file a motion to vacate\u2014\nthat is, to throw out\u2014the order\u201d\nof the United States Circuit Court\nof Appeals.\nDrug Firms\u2019 Lobby\nSpent More Than\nReal Estate Lobby\nWashington (LPA) Sure, un\nionists know all about lobbies. But\ndo you know what big-business\ngroup spent the largest lump sum\nfighting social legislation in the\nfirst three quarters of this year?\nIt\u2019s not the private power inter\nests, or the real estate-landlord\ncombine, nor even the Committee\nfor Constitutional Gov\u2019t, which\nfights for tax reductions and re\nstrictions on labor.\nThe Nat\u2019l Physicians\u2019 Committee\nis the top spender, according to the\nreports it has filed with Congress.\nTo fight health insurance\u2014which\nNPC culls \u201csocialized medicine\u201d\u2014\nthe committee has spent $353,990\nduring the first nine months of\n1948, according to its own reports.\nIronically enough, NPC expend\nad this sum, larger than its entire\n1947 budget, at a time when the\nWagner-Murray-Dingell health in\nsurance bill didn\u2019t stand the ghost\n)f a chance of passing the Republi\ncan-dominated Congress.\nThe physicians of the country\ndon\u2019t put up all the cash to run the\nanti-health insurance lobby. About\none- third of the NPC\u2019s funds dur\ning the first half of this year were\ncontributed by 20 large drug firms.\nThey put up $98,000 out of the\n$240,727.06 spent by NPC in that\ntime.\nVA PLANS DIVIDENDS\nFOR GI INSURANCE\nNew York.\u2014The Veterans Ad\nministration is preparing to pay\nmillions of veterans of World War\nII a dividend payment on their Na\ntional Service Life Insurance with\nin the year.\nHarold W. Braining, Assistant\nAdministrator for Insurance, in\nmaking known the method of pay\nment of the dividend, said the ex\nact amount of surplus in the NSLI\nfund was not known. Reliable\nsources estimate it between $1,000,\n000,000 and $2,000,000,000. Assets\nof the fund as of June 30 were $6,\n959,429,226.\nconsecu*\nACTUAL charges for 500\nfive funerals conducted by the\nDAWSON Funeral Home are as\nfollowsl\n10\u00b0A Were\n9% Were\n50% Were\n31% Were\nUnder SltO\nUnder $300\nUnder $500\nOver $500\nFuneral Home\nMuch Im\nso mti\u00ab\"\n215 West Fifth Street Phone Main 10\nThe most frequent problem which\narises in states where the injured\nworker has the right to choose his\nown physician, is when after receiv\ning a certain amount of treatment,\nhe is informed by his doctor that\nthe insurance company has direct\ned him to end treatment. This dir\nective by the insurance company is\nusually baswl upon the opinion of\none of its own doctors that further\ntreatment is not needed.\nWhen the worker\u2019s physician is\nin agreement with this opinion, it\npresents no problem. But very fre\nquently, the worker\u2019s doctor feels\nthat further treatment is still nec\nessary but in view of the company\u2019s\ndirective, he feels that he must\nsuspend treatment because further\nmedical bills would not be honored.\nThis ,is a strategic device fre\nquently employed by insurance\nfirms. The worker is entitled to\ncompensation only so long as there\nis medical evidence of a continuing\ndisability. This medical evidence\nconsists either of direct testimony\nby a physician at a hearing or by\nmedical reports. When there is a\ncessation of medical treatment,\nthere is necessarily a cessation of\nmedical reports. At a hearing, the\ncompany then is in a position to\nMEBA SETTLES WITH\nSHIPPERS ON COAST\nSan Francisco (LPA) Marine\nEngineers Beneficial Ass\u2019n reached\na separate agreement with west\ncoast shipowners last week and\nstepped out of the nine-week-old\nmaritime strike in Pacific ports.\nThe four unions remaining on the\npicket lines include Int\u2019l Longshore\nmen\u2019s Warehousemen\u2019s Union\nand Marine Cooks Stewards.\nWaterfront employers refuses to\nbargain with the four unions until\ntheir officers sign non-Communist\naffidavits under the Taft-Hartley\nact. Officers of MEBA, as well as\nMarine Firemen, Oilers Wipers\nwho reached agreement with the\nshipowners earlier, have signed the\naffidavits.\nThe settlement gives the ship en\ngineers $18 to $35 a month raises.\nCONSOLIDATES\nWashington (LPA)\u2014Gloria Kap\nlan and Arthur Riordan, both as\nsistant editors of CIO News, wert\nmarried Oct. 15 in Alexandria, Va.\nRiordan, former president of the\nPhiladelphia-C a mden Newspaper\nGuild, came to the News staff after\nthe demise of the Philadelphia\nRecord.\nTHE POTTERS HERALD\nPHONE WORKERS HIT THE CEMENT\u2014Communication Work\nof America picketed dozens of exchanges of Michigan Bell Tele-\ners\nphone Co. when the company stalled on wage demands. (.1. to r.) Pat\nricia Robertson, Doris Derkay and Doris Steenrood were all suspended\nfrom their jobs because of their picketing activities. Now the wages\ndispute is being arbitrated.\nWorkmen's Compensation Laws\nNo. 6 in a series of 12 articles\nby MAX L.\nTHE INJURED WORKER AND\nHIS DOCTOR\nWorkmen\u2019s compensation\u2019 bene\nfits are of two kinds\u2014the monetary\ncompensation for lost time and the\nmedical care rendered. In many\nways the\nthan the\nworker is\nis unable\nwork.\nments are always less than a work\ners\u2019 earnings, he sustains a net\nmonetary loss for the time during\nwhich he is unable to work. It,\ntherefore, becomes vitally import\nant for an injured worker to under\nstand the practical aspect of medi\ncal care.\nlatter is more important\nformer, since until the\ncured of his injuries, he\nto return to his regular\nSince compensation pay-\nKATZMAN\ncontend that it need not pay furth\ner compensation because there are\nno further medical reports estab\nlishing further disability.\nDoctors who have considerable\nexperience with compensation, fre\nquently continue with the treat\nment in spite of the carrier\u2019s dir\nective to suspend, and hope to re\nceive payment by establishing at a\nhearing before a Compensation Re\nferee or Commissioner, that the\ntreatment was necessary and the\nbill rendered was reasonable. Work\ners who have this type of doctor\nare fortunate.\nWhere a doctor refuses to con\ntinue treatment, though treatment\nis indicated, workers have the right\nto go to another doctor and obtain\nthe necessary treatment. If a work\ner finds that no doctor is available\nin view of the company\u2019s directive,\nthe worker, where possible, should\npay for his own treatment and seek\nreimbursement at a compensation\nhearing.\nIn states where hearings can be\nquickly obtained, a better plan is\nto request an immediate hearing\nfor the purpose of obtaining a find\ning from the Referee or Commis\nsioner as to whether further treat\nment is indicated. If such a finding\nis obtained, the company then has\nno alternative but to authorize such\nfurther treatment.\nIn states where the worker does\nnot have a free choice of physician,\nthis situation arises with even\ngreater frequency since the insur\nance company has greater control\nof the physician. A worker in such\na situation can follow the procedure\ndescribed above. In any event, if a\nworker feels that he is still unable\nto return to work, he should get\nfurther treatment, even if he has\nto pay for it himself. It can not be\nrepeated too many times that with\nout treatment, there can be no re\nports and without medical reports,\nthere can be no compensation.\nOBITUARIES\nMRS. KATHRYN DAILEY\nMrs. Kathryn Dailey, widow of\nEdward Dailey, died Nov. 2 in City\nHospital, following a short illness.\nMrs. Dailey came to East Liver\npool about 48 years ago. She was a\nfinisher by trade and employed last\nat the Homer Laughlin Qhina Co.\nShe will be remembered by many\nthroughout the trade for the active\nrole she played in affairs of Local\nUnion No. 53, having represented\nthat group at numerous conven\ntions and wage conferences.\nShe was a member of St. Aloy\nsios Catholic Church,. Court Dunne\n937, Catholic Daughters of America\nand the National Brotherhood of\nOperative Potters.\nSurvivors include a sister, Mrs.\nMary B. McConnell of New Brigh\nton and two nieces.\nServices were held from St.\nAloysius Catholic Church. Burial\nwas in St. Aloysius cemetery.\nBuy Union-Made goods from\nothers as you would have them\npay Union wages unto you I\nEAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\nEconomic\nHappenings That Affect the Dinner\nPails, Dividend ('hecks and Tax\nBills of Every Individual National\nand International Problems Insep\narable From Local Welfare\nThere has been very little per\nsonal mudslinging in the 1948\npresidential campaign, and prac\ntically none of the undercover rum\nor movements which are designed\nto persuade the electorate that this\ncandidate or that is morally, men\ntally, or physically unfit for office.\nMost of the critical digs have been\nof a general nature\u2014as, for in\nstance, Mr. Truman\u2019s description of\nthe 80th Congress as one of the\nworst in history, and Mr. Dewey\u2019s\nallegations that the present Ad\nministration is incapable of doing\nan efficient job. Thus, judged by\npolitical precedents, the campaign\nhaft been unusually clean, arid no\none of importance has attempted to\nmake either of the principal candi\ndates appear to be a crook of the\nfirst water.\nA good many, voters, perhaps,\nwill look back with nostalgic regret\non campaigns in which invective\ngave color and life to the proceed\nings, reprehensible as these weap\nons may be in principle. And to find\nthe campaigns which were most\nenlivened in this fashion, we must\nlook back quite a distance. In the\nOctober issue of the American Mer\ncury, Robert Bendiner presents an\namusing and instructive brief ac\ncount of \u201cMudslinging In National\nElections\u201d which indicates how\ntremendously the times have chang\ned in the matter of political man\nners and weapons.\nEven Washington was not spar\ned from the vitriol. On the First\nPresident\u2019s retirement, a news\npaper observed that \u201cIf ever a na\ntion has been debauched by a man,\nthe American nation has been de\nbauched by Washington.\u201d And,\nwhile he was in office, an opposi\ntion cartoon was published which\nshowed the Father of His Country\nbeing led to the guillotine.\nJefferson, sainted as he is in\nthese days, also came in for his\nshare of attack. The then president\nof Yale warned the country sole\nmply that the Jeffersonian doctrine\nwas designed to make \u201cour wives\nand'daughters the victims of legal\nprostitution.\u201d He was also accused,\nthrough a published tract, of being\na man of very loose morals.\nThe opposition really turned on\nthe blow-torches when Andrew\nJackson ran. Due to a legal mix\nup, the General had married his\nseCon^ wife,before she was fully\ndivorced from her first husband,\nand a second ceremony had been\nnecessary. An example of the use\nhis political ememies made of this\nincident is found in this sentence:\n\u201cOught a convicted adulteress and\nher paramour husband to be placed\nin the highest offices of this free\nami Christian land?\u201d\nIn modern times, Grover Cleve\nland, when running against Blaine,\nwas given the most savage treat\nment. Evidence was dug up to the\nHighlights\neffect that he was possibly the\nfather of an illegitimate child. This\nwas played to the hilt by the Re\npublicans, in the hope that the vot\ners would become convinced that\nhe was an utter libertine. As the\nNew York Sun put it, \u201cWe do not\nbelieve the American people will\nknowingly elect to the presidency\na coarse debauchee who will bring\nhis harlots with him to Washing\nton and hire lodgings for them con\nvenient to the White House.\u201d How\never, Cleveland\u2019s great record of\nprobity and public service\u2014coupled\nwith the fact that Blaine had a very\ndubious Congressional background\n-\u2014\u2018was sufficient to offset this. Yet\nit was very close\u2014a switch of a\nfew hundred votes in New York\nwould have beaten him. In this\nconnection, it is an interesting fact\nthat another piece of invective may\nhave been the determining factor.\nOne Republican slogan held that\nthe Democrats were the party of\n\u201cRum, Romanism and Rebellion.\u201d\nThis is supposed to have alienated\nthe large Catholic vote in New\nYork, and thus given Cleveland\nthe state.\nAl Smith came in for heavy\nabuse too. A clergyman asked rhe\ntorically: \u201cShall dry America elect\na cocktail President?\u201d A pamphle\ndescribed the Governor as \u201cthe\nfriend of prostitution.\u201d The Catho\nlic issue was played up to the hilt.\nHerbert Hoover and the responsible\nRepublicans had no part in this\nand considered such tactics con\ntemptible. But they couldn\u2019t stop\nthe vilification. And Mr. Hoover\ndidn\u2019t get off scot free by any\nmeans. He was accused of fraud\nduring his engineering career and\nother crimes.\nTo come down to the very recent\npast, Franklin Roosevelt was a con\nsistent target of the rumor mong\ners. A lunatic fringe put out pamp\nhlets to the effect that he was real\nly Jewish, was a sufferer from un\nmentionable diseases, and so on.\nScurrilous attacks were made on\nMrs. Roosevelt. Matters went so\nfar that the late President once\nsaid that his enemies \u201chave not\nbeen content with attacks on me,\nor on my wife, or on my sons\u2014no,\nnot content with that, they now in\nclude my dog Fala.\u201d Oddly enough,\nthat was literally true, Fala being\naccused of viciousness and other\ncanine sins.\nIt is a point of interest that vit\nriolic attack has been employed\nmost freely and consistently\nagainst the more dynamic and col\norful candidates\u2014Jefferson, Cleve\nland, Roosevelt, etc. This caused\nMr. Bendiner to say in his Mercury\narticle, \u201cGiven the comparatively\ncolorless pair of nominees we have,\nit was improbable from the start\nthat the 1948 affair would ever dip\nto the low but gaudy level of past\nclassics. Thus, the emphasis\nhas pretty much been on issues and\nprinciples rather than on personal\nities. But it\u2019s a safe bet that dur\ning some future election the mud\nslingers will dredge up the old\nammunition again.\nAustrian Workers Strive For Economic\nRecovery, Visiting Trade Unionist Says\nWashington (LPA)\u2014Reconstruc\ntion of Austria\u2019s war-damaged|settlement for Austria is Russia*\nplants, rebuilding her bombed cit\nies, and improving the diet of the\nworkers Union, a member of the\nAustria\u2019s trade unions today, de\nclared union leader Franz Olah\nlast week.\nOlah, who is secretary of the\nAustrian Construction Wood\nworkers Union, a member of the\nexecutive council of the Austrian\nTrade Union Federation, and a\nSocialist member of the Vienna\nCity Council, is on his way to the\nA FL convention in Cincinnati. He\nis the first Austrian labor leader\nto attend, as a fraternal delegate,\nan American union convention.\nEight of the 11 years that Aus\ntrian anil then Germah fascism\nruled his native land he spent in\njails and concentration camps.\nAustria was fortunate, he said,\nin achieving, with the permission\nof nil the war-time allies, economic\nand political unity .This was at\ntained despite its occupation by\nthe four powers\u2014US, Great Bri\ntain, France and Soviet Russia.\nTherefore, Olah thinks, Vienna will\nnot become the scene of another\nBerlin blockade, altho it, like Ber\nlin, is a four-power occupation area\nin the heart of a Russian zone.\nAustrian labor has preserved its\nfree trade union movement, and its\nown workers\u2019 Socialist Party, even\nin the Soviet zone, unlike the east\nern Germans who have been forced\nto accept Communist domination of\nboth their industrial and political\norganizations, Olah pointed out.\nThe Austrian workers in 1934,\nOlah proudly reminded reporters,\nwere the first people in the world\nto take up arms' against fascism.\nThis militant tradition prevented\nthe corruption of the workers\u2019\nmovements when Hitler occupied\nAustria, and has kept the unions\nfree from Communist domination\ndespite the fact that most of in\ndustrial Austria is \u201cbehind the iron\ncurtain\u201d today, the labor spokes\nman declared.\nBiggest barrier to a final peace\ndemand for what the Soviets call\n\u201cGerman external assets\u201d in Aus\ntria. Olah said that the Russians\nare insisting that Austrian indus\ntries stolen by the Nazis must be\nregarded as German property, and\ntherefore available for confiscation\nus reparations. But, Olah quipped,\n\u201cthe Germans didn\u2019t put the oil\ninto the ground. It belongs to the\nAustrian workers.\u201d Much as they\nwant a treaty and an end to the\noccupation the Austrian unions will\nnot acquiesce in permanent Soviet\nseizure of the workshops.\nThe Austrian unions belong to\nthe World Federation of Trade Un\nions, Olah stated. He complained,\nhowever, that the WFTU has given\nthe Austrian workers too much ad\nvice, and no assistance on the \u201cex\nternal assets problem.\u201d\nLouis Saillant, secretary of the\nWFTU, came to Austria and tried\nto tell the Austrian workers what\n\u201cactivities\u201d they should engage in,\nOlah recounted. \u201cBut,\u201d he said, \u201cwe\ngot no action from Saillant and the\nWFTU when we asked that the\nproblem of the \u2018external assets\u2019 be\nconsidered by that body.\u201d\n\u201cThe Austrian workers have al\nways believed in the importance of\na real international federation of\nlabor,\u201d their representative said,\n\u201cbut we want. an international\nwhich is clearly devoted to cooper\nation and democratic principles.\u201d\nWholesale Prices Up\n4.6% Above Year Ago\nWashington. Average primary\nmarket prices advanced 0.3 per\ncent during the week ended Octo\nber 23, 1948, according to the Bur\neau of Labor Statistics. The bur\neau\u2019s comprehensive index increas\ned to 165.3 percent of the 1926\naverage as the result of moderate\nprice increases for fresh meats and\nlivestock. It was 2 percent below\nthe level of four weeks ago but 4.6\npercent above the corresponding\nweek of a year ago.\nr.ME\nC. (ILNS).\u2014\nof Agriculture\ngood times for\nwith continued\nAn unofficial report prepared for\nfield workers and state agricultural\nextension workers in advising\nfarmers on future crop operations\nregarded full employment as a\n\u201cdistict possibility\u201d during the next\n6 years despite\ndownward price\nlikelihood of some\ntrends.\nwould not neces\nadverse effect on\nemployment, the\nLower prices\nsarily have an\nproduction _and\nreport said.\u2019Such prices, it explain\ned, might enable consumers to buy\n10 percent more goods and services\nthan this year and 50 percent more\nthan before \u2019the war.\nThe report added that a recession\nwith perhaps 10 percent fewer jobs\nand a 25 percent decline in incomes\nwould decrease purchasing power\nby only about 5 percent because of\nTEAM UP\n'pedenat\nOF EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\n...the famous criminal lawyer, whose\ngrand passion causes him to gamble his\ncareer, his marriage and his reputation\nin London\u2019s Old Bailey courtroom.\nCHARLES\nLAUGHTON\n.is die icy-blooded jurist whose high\nposition does not leave him immune\nto the charms of either the exotic Mrs.\nPsradine or the lovely Mrs. Keane.\nETHEL?\nBARRYMORE\n...is the judge's oppressed, fear-rid*\nden wife, who baa a bizarre motive\nfor protecting the involved Mrs. Para*\ndine from the vengeance of the law.\nl/atti.'\n...playa Mrs. Paradine,who is charged\nwith murdering her blind husband.\nHer incredible beauty and sincere\ngrief are powerful weapons of defense.\nThursday, November 4, 1948\nEconomists See Full Employment^\nGood Times For/Next Six Years\nWashington, D.\nU. S. Department\neconomists foresee\nthe next 6 years,\nhigh employment and lower prices.\nEven if there should be a moderate\nrecession, they think living stand\nards would remain far above the\n1935-39 prewar level.\nan accompanying substantial drop\nin prices.\nAnother report, summarizing\ncomments by department farm an\nalysts at the annual outlook con\nference of state agricultural repre\nsentatives, declared average net in\ncomes of farm operators might fall\nas much as 42 percent, or 22 per\ncent even under \u201cthe most favor\nable\u201d conditions, during the coming\n6 years.\nDebt Delinquency Is Danger\nSuch a decline, the analysts said,\nwould force a \u201csubstantial number\nof operators to seek government\nassistance in avoiding debt delin\nquency.\u201d\n\u201cBoth sets of reports are consist\nent,\u201d a department spokesman ex\nplained. \u201cThe nationwide outlook is\nfor living standards to stay far\nabove the 1935-39 prewar level. An\nalysts who discuss the possibility1\nof a drop in farmers\u2019 incomes note\nthat even a drop of 42 percent\nwould still keep the level consider-*\nably above prewar.\u201d ..t,.\nDemand the Union Label.\nCERAMIC\nOne Week Commencing Sunday\nDAVID 0. SEL2NICK S productien ef ALFRED HITCHCOCK\u2019S\nAND LOAN ASSOCIATION\n1032 Pennsylvania Avenue\nPARADIN E\u00ab*\nANN\niz Keane's wife, who fears\nthe allure of Mrs. Paradine, but\ngallantly supports her husband\u2019s\nheroic efforts to save her rival.\nCHARLES 1\nCOBURN\n...is the loyal friend of the family\nwhose efforts to salvage Keane's mar*\nriage embroil both men more deeply\nin the tangled past of Mrs. Paradine,\nLOUIS\nJOURDAN\n...ia the late Col. Paradine\u2019i valet, a\nsullen, smouldering introvert who\nhas only contempt for the law and a\nmysterious hold on Mrs. Paradine.\nNEWS OF THE DAY\nContinuous Show\nSaturday\nand\nSunday\nNOW SHOWING THROUGH SATURDAY\n\"SOUTHERN YANKEE\"\nstarring Red Skelton and Brian Donlevy\nSB","height":"26145","width":"21123"}}
